It should make no difference in how you use the object between :

void foo( arma:::cx_mat m ) ;
void foo( const arma::cx_mat& m ) ;

inside foo, you use m exactly the same way. Although the const here is 
there to protect you from yourself. Having the const here means that 
inside foo you are only allowed to call const methods of the 
arma::cx_mat class, so you can't modify the object.

If you want to be able to modify the object, you could use

void foo( arma::cx_mat& m ) ;

